# RevivifAI — General Code Standards

These standards apply to **all** programming languages in this repo (application code, configs, infra-as-code where relevant). For Python specifics, also follow `.cursor/rules/revivifai-python-standards.mdc`.

## Comments

- Keep comments **succinct** and **technical**: explain *whys* and non-obvious *whats*, not what the syntax already shows.
- Comments should read like polished internal documentation: keep them **grammatically correct**, with consistent tense, and free of typos.

## Correctness and efficiency

- Prefer clear, minimal solutions that are **correct by construction**: handle edge cases, validate assumptions at boundaries, and avoid speculative “fixes” that obscure behavior.
- Target **bug-free** delivery: test critical paths, fail loudly on invalid state, and do not merge known defects.
- Aim for implementations that are **maintainable and obviously right**—work you and reviewers can take **immense satisfaction** in owning, operating, and extending.

## Testing

- **Distinguish unit tests from integration tests**: unit tests isolate small units with controlled doubles and fast feedback; integration tests exercise real boundaries (I/O, processes, external services) with clear scope and stability expectations.
- **Use the latest test libraries and conventions** for the stack (assertion style, fixtures, async patterns, coverage, CI hooks)—verify against upstream docs rather than copying outdated examples.
- **Do not bend tests around broken behavior**: assert what production should do; when behavior is wrong, fix the code or explicitly document and ticket a known gap—do not lock in defects with permissive expectations.

## Research and editing

- Always perform **online research** before implementing new features to verify APIs, package versions, documentation, etc.
- Prefer **small, sequential edits** over re-generating entire files.

## Console and shell (agent runs)

- **Run terminal and console commands outside the sandbox** (full host permissions / non-sandboxed execution) as the default for this repo. The goal is the same working directory, environment, network, and tooling the developer uses—so installs, tests, `git`, and similar commands behave predictably and do not fail for artificial restriction reasons.
- If a step must run in a restricted environment, say so in the same turn and keep that exception narrow.

## Forward-looking codebase

- **Backwards compatibility is not a default requirement.** Prefer a clean API, unified abstraction, and decisive refactoring over preserving shims and legacy patterns.
- **Accept breaking changes** when they reduce complexity and tech debt—update call sites, configs, and docs accordingly.

## Performance

- **Do not shy away from legitimate optimizations** when they measurably matter or clearly reduce hot-path cost: e.g. bitwise operations where appropriate, memoization/caching, batching I/O, choosing better algorithms or data structures.
- **Prefer mature libraries** for well-scoped problems (parsing, crypto, serialization, HTTP, etc.) instead of hand-rolling subtle logic—after verifying license, maintenance, and fit.

## Security (production code and environments)

- Treat **security as a default requirement**, not an add-on: least privilege, safe defaults, strict validation of untrusted input, and secrets only via approved mechanisms (never in source control).
- **Do not introduce or leave known vulnerabilities**: keep dependencies patched; avoid deprecated/insecure APIs; use vetted primitives (e.g. established crypto and auth libraries, not custom schemes).
- Align with **OWASP Secure Coding Practices** and use the project checklist as a working reference: [OWASP Secure Coding Practices — Checklist](https://owasp.org/www-project-secure-coding-practices-quick-reference-guide/stable-en/02-checklist/05-checklist.html).

When security trade-offs arise, choose the conservative option and document the threat model briefly if non-obvious.
